00:00:04,190 --> 00:00:07,101
Following Week 3, are you ready
to start considering

2
00:00:07,301 --> 00:00:10,801
what type of treatment technologies
are appropriate in your city?

3
00:00:12,313 --> 00:00:14,453
Important concepts that you
learned this week

4
00:00:14,653 --> 00:00:17,405
for evaluating appropriate
treatment technologies

5
00:00:17,605 --> 00:00:21,292
include the level of technology
development established

6
00:00:21,492 --> 00:00:24,365
transferring or innovative. 

7
00:00:24,565 --> 00:00:27,215
We have grouped technologies
as established

8
00:00:27,415 --> 00:00:31,367
if there is enough operating
experience, the design considerations

9
00:00:31,567 --> 00:00:35,331
and operations and maintenance
requirements are established

10
00:00:35,531 --> 00:00:36,369
and can be recommended. 

11
00:00:37,158 --> 00:00:39,523
We have grouped technologies
as transferring,

12
00:00:39,723 --> 00:00:42,026
if knowledge is currently
being transferred

13
00:00:42,226 --> 00:00:44,630
from other sectors like waste
water treatments.

14
00:00:44,830 --> 00:00:47,461
And we have grouped technologies
as innovative

15
00:00:47,661 --> 00:00:51,799
if they show promise but are in
the research and development phase.

16
00:00:51,999 --> 00:00:55,330
These distinctions are very
important because they will have

17
00:00:55,530 --> 00:00:59,167
a direct impact on implementation
and the required

18
00:00:59,367 --> 00:01:02,532
level of management and partnerships
for scaling up,

19
00:01:02,732 --> 00:01:06,396
such as private partner partnerships
or with research institutes.

20
00:01:07,265 --> 00:01:11,435
Another important concept
that you learned is about linking

21
00:01:11,635 --> 00:01:14,435
treatment technologies
by their treatment objectives.

22
00:01:14,635 --> 00:01:18,215
Frequently a treatment chain
will include a combination

23
00:01:18,415 --> 00:01:22,278
of treatment technologies, depending
on the overall treatment objectives.

24
00:01:22,478 --> 00:01:25,574
This was also illustrated in
the design example

25
00:01:25,774 --> 00:01:29,718
of the Lubigi Faecal Sludge
Treatment Plant in Kampala, Uganda.

26
00:01:30,631 --> 00:01:33,217
This is why in the engineering
design approach

27
00:01:33,417 --> 00:01:36,490
the first steps include defining
treatment objectives

28
00:01:36,690 --> 00:01:38,204
so that you know what you
are designing

29
00:01:38,404 --> 00:01:40,437
treatment technologies for.

30
00:01:41,133 --> 00:01:45,458
Once you have defined treatment end
goals or resource recovery options

31
00:01:45,658 --> 00:01:49,797
then you can simultaneously consider
the treatment objectives necessary

32
00:01:50,041 --> 00:01:54,251
 to achieve them together with
the level of technology development

33
00:01:54,451 --> 00:01:58,848
which is important for the associated
level of required management.

34
